/*

Selecting the HTML elements
const form = document.getElementById("productForm");
const status = document.getElementById("status");

 What happens here:

document.getElementById("productForm") → selects the <form> element with id="productForm".

document.getElementById("status") → selects the element where you’ll display success/error messages.

=========================================================================================================

 Handling the form submission
form.addEventListener("submit", async (e) => {
  e.preventDefault();

 Explanation:

When the user clicks “Add Product”, this event listener runs.

e.preventDefault() stops the form from doing its default behavior (which would reload the page).

We handle the submission using JavaScript (AJAX) instead.

=============================================================================

Creating the product object
const product = {
  name: document.getElementById("name").value,
  price: Number(document.getElementById("price").value),
  image: document.getElementById("image").value,
  description: document.getElementById("description").value
};

Explanation:

Reads the values entered by the admin into the form fields.

Converts the price to a number (Number(...)) since form inputs return strings.

Packs everything into an object like:

{
  name: "Air Jordan 1",
  price: 4999,
  image: "https://cdn.example.com/jordan1.jpg",
  description: "Classic high-top sneakers with premium leather."
}


This object will be sent to the backend.

=========================================================================================================

 Sending the POST request to backend
const response = await fetch("http://localhost:5000/api/products", {
  method: "POST",
  headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
  body: JSON.stringify(product)
});

 Explanation:

Uses fetch() to make a POST request to your backend API endpoint /api/products.

headers tell the server you’re sending JSON data.

body sends the product object as a JSON string.

 On your backend (likely Node + Express), you’ll have something like:

app.post("/api/products", (req, res) => {
  const newProduct = req.body;  // parsed JSON
  // save newProduct to database (MongoDB, MySQL, etc.)
});

